</head>

<a name="top"></a>
<p class="dateline">Tuesday, February 10, 2009</p>
      
<p class="headline">Spaniards and their Latin American cousins: Racist Culture in Sports</p>

<p><img src="http://www.solitaryone.com/images/articles/2009/02/ArgentineWomenFootballSlantEyes.jpg" alt="Argentinian women footballers Maria Potassa, 
Eva Gonzalez, Fabiana Vallejos and Andrea Ojeda (pictured left to right) make slant-eye gesture mocking Asians." title="Argentinian women footballers 
Maria Potassa, Eva Gonzalez, Fabiana Vallejos and Andrea Ojeda (pictured left to right) make slant-eye gesture mocking Asians."> <br />
<span class="body7">Argentinian women footballers Maria Potassa, Eva Gonzalez, Fabiana Vallejos and Andrea Ojeda (pictured left to right).</span> </p>

<p>I've been away for a while, but there's nothing that gets the blogging juices flowing again like another example of Spanish ignorance
and racism, or in this case that of their Argentinian cousins. </p>

<p>This is an incident that occurred back in August of 2008, during the Olympics, but I don't think it got much notice. I just accidentally
came across it recently. </p>

<p>I had written about the <a href="http://www.solitaryone.com/?page=articles/2008/08/20080813">Spanish men's national 
basketball team making slant-eye gestures</a> back in August of 2008. (It was, as a matter of fact, my first post on this blog.) Then
there was the <a href="http://www.solitaryone.com/?page=articles/2008/08/20080815">Spanish Federation cup team doing the same.</a> 
Not to be outdone by the athletes, the <a href="http://www.solitaryone.com/?page=articles/2008/10/20081030">Spanish F1 racing 
fans decided to get in on the racist act</a>. Now, granted they're not Spanish, but the former Spanish colony of Argentina is displaying
it's affinity for the old country. Is there a cultural pattern emerging here? </p>

<p>With no need to restate all the comments I've made regarding this topic, but simply to state the facts with regards to this particular
incident: Members of the Argentinian women's soccer (football) team, Maria Potassa, Eva Gonzalez, Fabiana Vallejos and Andrea Ojeda,
were photographed making the slant-eye gesture that is used to mock Asians. The photo was published in a South American sports newspaper
Ole days before the 2008 Beijing Olympics. The details can be found in this <a href="http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Argentinian-Womens-Football-Team-Make-Slant-Eyed-Gestures-In-Olympic-Photograph/Article/200808315082256"
target="_blank">Sky News article</a>. </p>

<p>As a further sign of the extent of this problem, John Terry, the captain of the English team has said that he will lead his
team off the field in support, if the referee decided to take action against Spanish fans' racism in their upcomming Wednesday match. This after their experience
during a 2004 friendly against Spain when fans directed racist chants at Shaun Wright-Phillips and Ashley Cole. You can read the full
details in this <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/england/4583436/England-vow-to-stand-up-to-racist-chants.html" target="_blank">
Telegraph article</a>. </p>

<p>Whether there's an undercurrent of racism in Spanish culture, as well as numerous others, there are too many examples of these types
of racist incidents involving Spanish athletes and fans for them to be isolated incidents or outliers. There have been numerous articles
that have argued that Spanish society seems more tolerant of these expressions of racism in sports, since similar situations are not as commonly seen
in other European countries. </p>

<p>Regardless, apparently racist behavior by the Spanish were not seen as isolated incidents since there were people that
found enough objectionable behavior by their athletes to have started a Facebook campaign to have Spain kicked out of the 2008 summer Olympics in Beijing. </p>  

<p>As usual, their defense (in this case Spain's Olympic tennis silver-medallist Anabel Medina Garrigues) was that they didn't see
it as a racist gesture. This is what is always said in defense of people who've caused offense, yet they never seem to be able to
grasp the concept that the offenders' intentions isn't the issue, but the consequences of their actions. A drunk driver doesn't
intend to kill someone while driving drunk, but that's of no relevance to the victim. </p>

<p></p>

<p></p>

<p></p>

<p class="keywords">Keywords: Argentina, Argentinian women's football soccer team, slant-eye gesture, racism </p>

<p>
