<meta name="keywords" content="Edgar Bronfman Sr. on holocausts, anti-Semitism, minority status, self-identity, Jewishness, Jewish identity, discrimination,
racism, ADL Anti-Defamation League, David Boreanaz, white ethnics, affirmative action" /> 
 
<!-- <meta name="section-id" content="2218" /> -->
 
<meta name="date" content="2008-12-18" />

<meta name="last-modified" content="2008-12-22T18:07-05:00" />
 
<meta name="title" content="Minority Status: Defined Externally vs. Internally" /> 
<!-- META DATA: END -->

</head>

<a name="top"></a>
<p class="dateline">Monday, December 18, 2008</p>
      
<p class="headline">Minority Status: Defined Externally vs. Internally</p>

<!-- <p class="floatleft"> </p> -->

<p>Very often in debates about racism, discrimination, affirmative action, etc., you will hear white ethnics (that's the technical term used in 
sociology, I believe) who don't understand complaints from minorities, express the belief that they are simply complaining and trying to 
find excuses, or gain an unfair advantage. The standard line is that when their ancestors immigrated to the United States from Ireland, Italy, etc.,
they were discriminated against, but they managed to pull themselves up by the bootstraps and integrate into society to achieve the American dream.</p>

<p>The problem with this view is that it shows a lack of understanding, or willful ignorance, of the basis of discrimination in American society.
Many don't want to face the fact that the discrimination in this society is based on culture, and more exclusively, race. </p>

<p>While it is true that many European immigrants faced discrimination during certain times in this country's history, that discrimination was based
on culture. Once these immigrants assimilated into American culture, that discrimination essentially went away. When the children of those immigrants were born
in America, and grew up speaking English without an accent and adopted American culture, they essentially became full-fledge members of the white-majority
club. In the early part of the century, there might have been some discrimination based on someone's European ethnicity, but that was temporary and has long faded.</p>

<p>The main basis for discrimination in this country is based on race. One example to illustrate this point is that of the father of actor David Boreanaz, of <i>Bones</i>
and <i>Buffy the Vampire Slayer</i> fame. According to David, when his father was hired for a Buffalo, New York TV station, he used the name Dave Thomas, as
opposed to his real name, because the station felt his real name was too "ethnic" (e.g. too Italian). The point of this story is that, as long as he was white, 
it didn't matter what his ethnic background was, since that was something that can be easily covered up. </p>

<p>On the other hand, during the historical 2008 U.S. presidential election, many voters, while being interviewed, said plainly that they could not
vote for someone with the name Barack Hussein Obama for president. I venture to guess that these people were not being completely honest (perhaps even to themselves). 
Even if Obama was named Lastings Milton Abercrombie, these people still would not have voted for him. They would still have voted for McCain, even if 
he had been born Vladimir Muhammad Chen Rodrigo. </p>

<p>The core sociological idea behind this is that, for white ethnics, identity is largely self-defined, especially given the prevalent miscegenation between white ethnics.
Therefore, for someone with Irish, German, Italian, Scottish and Greek ancestry, they can decide, somewhat arbitrarily, whether they want to define themselves as
Irish-American, Italian-American, etc. For racial minorities on the other hand, how they can be defined is written all over their faces. To wit, for white ethnics, minority
status is internally defined (not to mention irrelevant and superficial, i.e. of no social consequence), while that for racial minorities, it is externally defined and has an
effect on their opportunities and options.</p>  

<p>For many generations now, being of Jewish, Italian or Irish, etc., decent has not had any effect on a person's ability to rise to the highest positions in society, as too many
examples to cite unequivocally demonstrate. For racial minorities on the other hand, this is not the case. Although the election of Obama is a great step in the right direction,
an argument to the contrary using the result of the election, would be based on specious evidence. </p>

<p>This leads me to the last point, which is that of using some (white) ethnicity to try and claim minority status, or to deny that status to racial minorities. An example of this is
that of Jewish identity. Without commenting too much on this topic, lest I incur the wrath of the Anti-Defamation League, I will just say that the vast majority of Jews, being Jewish
in no way results in any discrimination (no more than to someone who is, for example, too short/fat/tall/etc.), as evidenced by the success many have achieved. No aspect of their daily lives
differs in any degree from that of any other white person in mainstream American society. The extremely high levels of amalgamation, often used by sociologists as a measure of integration, between Jews and white non-Jews,
is another indicator of how inextricable they are from white, mainstream society. So any attempt to claim minority status (and I am not claiming that most do, although some groups have, and done so very
successfully), would be, to some extent, self-delusional (or self-defined, i.e. not definited by society), thus making it hard for many on the outside to see what really distinguishes them from mainstream white America. 
(One exception that might have to be made is that of Orthodox Jews, who differ culturally, to a certain extent, from white mainstream society.) </p>

<p>I will simply quote Edgar Bronfman, Sr., who I think spoke in an incredibly insightful and forthright manner when he made the following comments in a
<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/05/magazine/05wwln-q4-t.html?ref=magazine" target="_blank">New York Times article</a>:</p>

<p><b>Why is it important to you that Judaism continues? </b>
There are things we have to do. For instance, Darfur, Cambodia, Rwanda. There have been holocausts since our Holocaust. We should be the first people to stand up and say this is unacceptable, 
but we don't. We say, "Never again," just for us. We have to say, No, it's for everyone, this "Never again."

<p><b>Why do you give your money to Jewish causes instead of broader social causes?</b>
There are not that many of us in the Jewish world who understand that we are in crisis. We are not in crisis because 
of anti-Semitism; we are in crisis because we are disappearing through assimilation. </p>

<p><b>How do you know that anti-Semitism is no longer a threat? </b>
I think the greatest evidence of that is when Al Gore lost but didn't lose the election in 2000, nobody blamed it on Joe Lieberman 
because Joe was a Jew. Nobody. I never heard that. </p>

<p>Others notable Jews, such as Noam Chomsky and Norman Finkelstein, have expressed similar views on Jewish identity, history, etc., and as a result, come under attack
from the ADL, Alan Dershowitz, and other like-minded individuals. </p>

<p class="keywords">Keywords: Edgar Bronfman Sr. on holocausts, anti-Semitism, minority status, self-identity, Jewishness, Jewish identity, discrimination,
racism, ADL Anti-Defamation League, white ethnics, affirmative action </p>

