<a name="top"></a>
<p class="dateline">Monday, November 17, 2008</p>
      
<p class="headline">A 146-year-old Civil War Continues: Some Southerners Cannot Accept Black President, Enhancing Calls for Secession</p>

<p>After the historic election of the first African-American president of the United States, white supremacist groups and hate crimes are on the rise.</p>

<p class="floatleft"><img src="http://www.solitaryone.com/images/articles/2008/11/confederate-soldiers.jpg" alt="Photograph of Confederate soldiers." 
title="Photograph of Confederate soldiers." /> </p>

<p>On November 12, I wrote about the negative reactions from a number of European politicians and journalists to the U.S. election. Not to be outdone, racists 
in the U.S. are stepping up their activities because they cannot accept having a black president. (I supported Obama for president because I think he will take the
country in a better direction than McCain. But if for no other reason, I'm glad that he won because of the satisfaction I get in knowning that all those racists out 
there are bugging out, as a result of having to deal with the fact that the new president of the country they live in is a black man.) </p>

<p><a href="http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/1117/p03s01-uspo.html" target="_blank">As reported in the Christian Science Monitor</a>,
hate crime incidents have spiked, and hate language has increased, since the election of Barack Obama as the 44th president of the United States. </p>

<p>The article reports that white supremacist and nationalist websites have seen a dramatic increase in hits: Stormfront and the Council of Conservative Citizens report 
that their servers have crashed because of heavy traffic. The League of the South, a secessionist group, says Web hits jumped from 50,000 a month to 300,000 since Nov. 4, 
and its phones are ringing off the hook. </p>

<p>The article points out that a there is a segment of this society that feels disenfranchised and politically marginalized, and that this, in part, is the cause for this
up tick in hate activity and language. Reports have also shown a dramatic increase in gun sales as a result of the election, such as 
<a href="http://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=6209255" target="_blank">this one from ABC News</a>. These white people who feel so marginalized and disenfranchised in America, 
at least some of them, must live with so much fear, and completely lack a sense of self-esteem and security. This is pathetic since whites inherently enter society facing
the fewest obstacles, at least on a racial level&#8212;which is often, though not always, correlated to a person's economic level.   

<p>Often, people in this country and in other places look at conflicts in the Middle East disdainfully, wondering how people could engage in sectarian violence over 
events and grudges from over one thousand years ago. Maybe as the old adage goes, they should take a look in the mirror. Even though the American Civil War has been 
technically over for over 140 years, there are still many who have not gotten over it. There are still active groups in this country who are still seeking secession
from the United States of America. These sentiments have also increase as a result of this historic election. There are still people who have not gotten over the idea
that slavery is wrong, though I'm sure they would not put it in those terms, even to themselves. More often, they portray it as a respect for "tradition," which is one
of those insidious code words, describing a longing for the good ol' days of, if not slavery, at least Jim Crow or segregation. </p>

<p>Unfortunately for those whites who feel threatened by the changing nature of American demographics, and see the political influence of the Deep South and the 
"Southern strategy" fading, time's tide is not on their side. As population projections show, in another generation or two, whites will become a minority in the U.S.
And to those whites who cannot accept the future and let go and move beyond their vision of the past, time's tide will smother you, and I will too. </p>  

<p>Here is just a small article roll of the anti-black and anti-Muslim (even though Obama has been a Christian his whole life) reactions against the election results:
<blockquote>
&#149; <a href="http://rawstory.com/rawreplay/?p=2451" target="_blank">Obama election "is sin against the Lord" because we have a &nbsp;&nbsp;"Muslim" president</a> <br />
&#149; <a href="http://rawstory.com/rawreplay/?p=2436" target="_blank">Lawsuits claim election night hate crimes by Chicago police</a> <br />
&#149; <a href="http://wcbstv.com/local/obama.bias.crime.2.858391.html" target="_blank">Cross burned on lawn of N.J. Obama Supporter</a> <br />
&#149; <a href="http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2008/11/staten_island_teen_gang_beat_m.html" target="_blank">Staten Island teen beaten while attackers shout 'Obama'</a> <br />
&#149; <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/10/27/obama.plot/" target="_blank">Tennessee men charged with plot to kill Obama</a> <br />
</blockquote> 
</p>

<p>The list is nowhere near exhaustive, and I'm sure is only a miniscule fraction of all the election-related hate crimes that have been committed as a result of the
election result. I certainly have come across too many reports to list here. </p>

<p class="keywords">Keywords: 2008 U.S. presidential elections, marginalized fringe groups, white supremacists, Ku Klux Klan, hate crimes, cross-burning, Southern whites,
Deep South, Stormfront, Council of Conservative Citizens, League of the South, Southern Poverty Law Center, Barack Obama</p>

<p>
