<a name="top"></a>
<p class="dateline">Wednesday, November 12, 2008</p>
      
<p class="headline">This Is The Real You: European Politicians React To U.S. Election, Revealing Racist Attitudes</p>

<p>Many politicians and ordinary people in Europe, as well as around the world, reacted positively and enthusiastically to the election of Barack Obama as the 
next president of the United State of America. This was the image that most Americans saw when broadcasts showed the reactions of people from around the world to
the 2008 U.S. presidential election. </p>

<p><img src="http://www.solitaryone.com/images/articles/2008/11/HitlerMussolini.jpg" width="486.864" height="291.2168" alt="Hitler and Mussolini" title="Hitler and Mussolini"> <br />
<span class="body7">Austrian Journalist Klaus Emmerich called Obama dangerous and implicitly compared him to Hitler.</span></p>

<p>However, what we weren't shown was the other side, those who reacted with racist remarks that reveal the attitude still held by many in Europe, the root of which
is a sense of white superiority and entitlement. </p>

<p>There are many aspects of Europe which is admirable, including scientific, cultural and social developments of the highest order. Many of their ideals are the 
most progressive in the world, especially those dealing with equality and democracy. Europe is one of the most democratic and free places on earth, with some of
the highest living standards (based on per capita GDP). However, the sense of superiority and entitlement is also another aspect of European culture, and they cannot
be allowed to be selective in which parts of their culture they want to accept and which parts they want to deny. </p>

<p>Despite these achievements, it should not cover up the fact that some aspects of European society have not lived up to these high ideals. Rumsfeld spoke about
"old and new Europe." He was referring to something else, but the terms can also be borrowed to describe racial attitudes in Europe. Racism is still prevalent,
as recognized by France's first lady, when she spoke about the election, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/12/world/europe/12europe.html?hp" target="_blank">
as reported in a NYTimes.com article</a>: 
<blockquote>
"The election of Barack Obama highlights via a cruel contrast the shortcomings of the French Republic and the distance that separates us from a country whose citizens 
knew how to go beyond the racial question," the manifesto said. It won support from Mr. Sarkozy's wife, Carla, who told Le Journal du Dimanche, "our prejudices are 
insidious" and hoped the "Obama effect" would help to reshape society.
</blockquote>
In another example, Britain has only 15 nonwhites in the 646-member House of Commons. </p>

<p>(The manifesto was in reference to one written by Yazid Sabeg of France, a millionaire child of Algerian immigrants, calling for affirmative-action programs to 
help realize the French ideal of equality in French society.) </p> 

<p>Here is just a sampling of some of the reactions of "old Europe" (as reported <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/10/AR2008111002810.html"
target="_blank">in this WashingtonPost.com article</a>):
<blockquote><u>Silvio Berlusconi, prime minister of Italy</u>: On Thursday, during a visit to Moscow, he praised Obama for being "young, handsome and even suntanned." Berlusconi's remark 
caused a stir in Italy, as critics chided him for sounding like a fool. But the prime minister was unrepentant. "What's the problem? It was a compliment," 
he told journalists the next day. Anyone who did not get the joke, he added, was an "imbecile." <br /> <br />

<u>National Democratic Party of Germany (neo-Nazi sympathizers)</u>: "Africa Conquers the White House," read a headline on their Web site. J&#252;rgen Gansel, a party 
leader and an elected lawmaker in the German state of Saxony, blamed Obama's victory on "the American alliance of Jews and Negroes." <br /> <br />

<u>Die Tageszeitung, a Berlin newspaper</u>: It published a large front-page photo of the White House under the headline, "Uncle Barack's Cabin." <br /> <br />

<u>Klaus Emmerich, well-known Austrian journalist</u>: "I think the Americans are still racists and they must be very badly off to so spectacularly -- and that has to be said, no doubt -- 
send a black man with a black, very good-looking and clever woman to the White House." After saying that he "wouldn't want the Western world to be directed by a black man," 
he added: "If you say that is a racist comment, you're right. Without a doubt." (At least he's honest about his racism; I salute him for that.) <br /> <br />

<u>Artur G&#243;rski, legislator from the Law and Justice party of Poland</u>: Obama is "the black messiah of the new Left" and a "crypto-communist" who would undoubtedly 
prove a "disaster." He added: "Al-Qaeda is rubbing their hands with glee that the new president wants peace, not war.... This marks the end of the white man's civilization.... 
America will soon pay a high price for this quirk of democracy."
</blockquote>

<p>The story is old, I know, but it goes one.</p>

<p class="keywords">Keywords: European politicians lawmakers, Barack Obama, U.S. presidential elections, racism, Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, Die Tageszeitung
Berlin newspaper, Uncle Barack's Cabin, Uncle Tom's Cabin, Harriet Beecher Stowe, Der Spiegel, German magazine, Yonis Ayeh, Initiative of Black People in Germany,
journalist Klaus Emmerich, Hitler, Poland lower house of Parliament, Artur G&#243;rski legislator Law and Justice Party, 2008 U.S. presidential election</p>
      
