<a name="top"></a>
<p class="dateline">Saturday, November 1, 2008</p>
      
<p class="headline">UPDATE: Step Aside Hitler's Germans, Here Come the Spanish F1 Fans (And an NY Ad Agency)!</p>

<p>As I wrote about in my October 30, 2008, post, a Web site was set up in Spain on which there were numerous posts filled with abusive and racist language 
directed at McLaren F1 driver Lewis Hamilton.</p>

<p>As an update, it turns out that the site was owned by the Spanish subsidiary of the New York-based advertising agency TWBA, a part of Omnicom, one of the largest
advertising agencies in the world. This was according to a report in <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3362526/Website-at-the-centre-of-racist-attacks-on-Lewis-Hamilton-is-owned-by-the-worlds-biggest-advertising-agency.html"
target="_blank">The Daily Telegraph</a>. </p>

<p>The degree to which the employees and management of the company were aware of what was being posted on their Web site, and the extent of their responsibility, 
can be open to further investigation and debated. A spokesperson in New York could not explain why the site was not monitored for racist and abusive content. 
What should be noted is that this type of racism can be easily, openly and publicly broadcasted on space owned and operated by a major corporation.  </p>

<p>Though no one who has a clear view of society should be surprised that such things exist, we should also not be surprised that there are those out there who
feel free to use a site belonging to an international corporation to post these  types of thoughts and views. What could be really worthwhile to consider, especially 
by people who are surprised by this incident, is a re-evaluation of the state of society, to gain a more realistic view of it. This way they can see how it is a society 
where these people feel perfectly comfortable in using a mainstream Web site to openly put up such posts, and one in which the owners did not feel the need to be vigilant 
and on the alert for such an occurrence. </p>

<p>In other words, despite a lot of lip service, racism is still not a very important issue in a lot of societies, not a subject worth being aware of. </p>

<p class="keywords">Keywords: F1, Formula One, Lewis Hamilton, Pincha la Rueda de Hamilton - Spanish for 'Burst Hamilton's Tyre',
racist, racism, Spain, Spanish, race hate campaign website, Brazilian Grand Prix, McLaren, Fernando Alonso, Felipe Massa, 
Circuit de Catalunya, TWBA Omnicom advertising agency</p>
      
<p>
